00:15:02,403 --> 00:15:03,945
Thank you, Calista.

239
00:15:07,324 --> 00:15:09,660
I think I may need to do
some damage control with Cathy.

240
00:15:09,744 --> 00:15:12,287
- Why?
- I've been trying to be deferential,

241
00:15:12,371 --> 00:15:14,874
but I think it's coming off
as patronizing.

242
00:15:14,956 --> 00:15:18,001
- Well, that was the risk.
- I know.

243
00:15:18,085 --> 00:15:20,045
Is she feeling threatened?

244
00:15:20,128 --> 00:15:23,173
Threatened, no.
Possibly overshadowed.

245
00:15:23,257 --> 00:15:26,677
I think I'm getting too much attention
and it's tough to be effective

246
00:15:26,761 --> 00:15:29,847
when I don't have Cathy on my team,
so I may need to win her over.

247
00:15:29,930 --> 00:15:32,683
Well, let's not forget
where the focus is tonight.

248
00:15:32,767 --> 00:15:35,811
Since when can't I do
two things at once?

249
00:15:35,895 --> 00:15:38,021
- You're crooked.
- What?

250
00:15:40,608 --> 00:15:43,819
- Ready for battle.
- Yes.

251
00:16:21,315 --> 00:16:23,567
The Vice President of the United States,
Donald Blythe.

252
00:16:23,651 --> 00:16:25,653
- Mr. President. Welcome.
- Mr. Vice President.

253
00:16:25,736 --> 00:16:28,196
Thank you.

254
00:16:28,280 --> 00:16:29,907
President Petrov, welcome.

255
00:16:29,990 --> 00:16:32,660
It's a pleasure.

256
00:16:32,743 --> 00:16:34,536
Hi. You look beautiful.

257
00:16:34,620 --> 00:16:36,371
Oh, it's serviceable.

258
00:16:36,455 --> 00:16:38,958
- You look fantastic, as always.
- Thank you.

259
00:16:39,040 --> 00:16:42,503
All eyes at the table
will be on you, not them.

260
00:16:44,296 --> 00:16:46,966
Senator Mendoza.
Soon to be candidate Mendoza.

261
00:16:47,048 --> 00:16:50,552
- The rumor mill begins.
- You started with Reagan, no?

262
00:16:50,636 --> 00:16:52,346
Staffed on his '84 campaign.

263
00:16:52,429 --> 00:16:55,432
He has a portrait of the Gipper
in his office wearing a cowboy hat.

264
00:16:55,516 --> 00:16:59,019
Hm. When men were men. Hm?

265
00:17:03,440 --> 00:17:06,276
Bob, I had a thought. Dave Blanchek
is on Armed Services and--

266
00:17:06,360 --> 00:17:09,070
I don't want to hold up the line.

267
00:17:09,154 --> 00:17:11,615
- Mr. President, a pleasure.
- I want to move Birch.

268
00:17:11,699 --> 00:17:13,408
Put Mendoza next to me instead.

269
00:17:13,492 --> 00:17:16,453
Alan. You clean up well.

270
00:17:16,537 --> 00:17:18,121
Class by association.

271
00:17:18,205 --> 00:17:19,957
- Where's your date?
- I don't have one.

272
00:17:20,040 --> 00:17:23,669
- I can walk you in too, if you'd like.
- No. Wouldn't want to ruin the picture.

273
00:17:26,296 --> 00:17:27,422
Ah, our special guests.

274
00:17:27,506 --> 00:17:29,216
I'm so delighted
you could be with us.

275
00:17:29,299 --> 00:17:31,426
Thank you so much for coming.
Mr. President.

276
00:17:31,510 --> 00:17:34,388
It's taken us too long
to sit at the same table.

277
00:17:34,471 --> 00:17:38,726
Did you discuss
our issues in the closed talks?

278
00:17:38,809 --> 00:17:40,143
We discussed many things.

279
00:17:40,227 --> 00:17:43,271
But specifically our concerns?

280
00:17:43,355 --> 00:17:45,691
Was anything on our list discussed?

281
00:17:45,774 --> 00:17:48,443
- Why don't we take a photo first?
- Good idea. Hm?

282
00:18:08,213 --> 00:18:10,925
Viktor, tell me. Are you in love?

283
00:18:11,008 --> 00:18:14,845
I don't know about...
love, but...

284
00:18:16,722 --> 00:18:19,433
I'm learning to enjoy being divorced.

285
00:18:26,440 --> 00:18:28,692
Which translates into:

286
00:18:28,776 --> 00:18:31,319
"Howdy, and please
don't steal the silverware."

287
00:18:34,031 --> 00:18:37,034
Now that I have exhausted
all of the Russian I know,

288
00:18:37,117 --> 00:18:40,704
Claire and I would like to welcome
all of you to the White House,

289
00:18:40,788 --> 00:18:45,960
as we host President Petrov
in this historic state visit.

290
00:18:46,043 --> 00:18:49,379
A century ago, a century and a half ago,

291
00:18:49,463 --> 00:18:54,468
de Tocqueville wrote, in regards
to America and Russia, the following:

292
00:18:54,551 --> 00:18:58,346
"Their point of departure
and their paths diverse,

293
00:18:58,430 --> 00:19:01,433
nevertheless, each seems called

294
00:19:01,516 --> 00:19:05,353
by some secret desire of Providence,

295
00:19:05,437 --> 00:19:10,776
to one day hold in their hands
the destinies of half the world."

296
00:19:10,859 --> 00:19:14,529
Well, I'd like to amend that tonight
and say, not just half the world,

297
00:19:14,613 --> 00:19:19,034
the entire world looks to us
for leadership.

298
00:19:19,118 --> 00:19:23,705
So, to President Petrov,
and all of the great things

299
00:19:23,789 --> 00:19:26,166
that our great nations
will do together.

300
00:19:26,249 --> 00:19:28,919
- Mr. President.
- Hear, hear!

301
00:19:35,843 --> 00:19:38,846
Which is Russian for,
"Never trust the French."

302
00:19:41,264 --> 00:19:45,310
And thank you to the president and First
Lady for your grace and hospitality.

303
00:19:45,393 --> 00:19:48,105
Now, a little more recently
than de Tocqueville,

304
00:19:48,188 --> 00:19:50,899
about, uh, 30 years ago,

305
00:19:50,983 --> 00:19:53,527
Mikhail Gorbachev came
to this very house

306
00:19:53,610 --> 00:19:57,197
and talked of an end
to our "winter of discontent."

307
00:19:58,573 --> 00:20:03,578
I think it's safe to say that
that winter seems far gone now.

308
00:20:03,662 --> 00:20:08,834
And here, on this beautiful May evening,
I welcome a "spring of enchantment."

309
00:20:08,917 --> 00:20:13,505
Now we all know which of you
brings the enchantment to the table.

310
00:20:14,089 --> 00:20:15,883
To you, Mrs. Underwood.

311
00:20:19,427 --> 00:20:22,931
- And, of course, your lesser half.
- Ah, thank you.

312
00:20:26,393 --> 00:20:31,190
Now I'd like to toast three others
in this room tonight.

313
00:20:31,272 --> 00:20:35,152
Nadya Tolokonnikova,
Masha Alyokhina,

314
00:20:35,235 --> 00:20:37,112
and Pyotr Verzilov.

315
00:20:37,196 --> 00:20:39,823
Now, I know we had our differences.

316
00:20:39,907 --> 00:20:43,744
But I also know they come
from something we all share:

317
00:20:45,162 --> 00:20:47,915
a deep love of our country.

318
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,669
To you. And to Russia.

319
00:20:53,879 --> 00:20:57,507
Mr. President, Nadya and Masha
would like to make a toast.

320
00:21:03,847 --> 00:21:06,975
To Viktor Petrov,
whose loyalty runs so deep

321
00:21:07,059 --> 00:21:08,852
he's given his friends
half of the country.

322
00:21:10,687 --> 00:21:13,982
Who's so open to criticism,
that most of his critics are in prison.

323
00:21:22,241 --> 00:21:24,243
You made your point.

324
00:21:25,202 --> 00:21:30,082
Now, please, sit and let us all

325
00:21:30,165 --> 00:21:33,794
drink and laugh,
like true Russians do. Hm?

326
00:21:46,473 --> 00:21:48,349
Well, Mr. President,

327
00:21:48,433 --> 00:21:52,562
this is proof why you made the
right decision never to have children.

328
00:22:00,570 --> 00:22:02,489
My staff prepped them.

329
00:22:02,572 --> 00:22:04,992
- They assured us.
- It's nothing.

330
00:22:05,075 --> 00:22:08,578
- I admire your grace.
- Please. Not another word.

331
00:22:10,247 --> 00:22:12,791
I knew Pussy Riot was a bad idea.

332
00:22:12,874 --> 00:22:15,794
- You should go.
- No. Best thing is not to comment.

333
00:22:15,877 --> 00:22:17,921
It lowers us to their level.

334
00:22:19,131 --> 00:22:20,674
Juice or soda?

335
00:22:20,757 --> 00:22:22,425
Diet something, if you got it.

336
00:22:23,802 --> 00:22:25,512
Who are they?

337
00:22:28,765 --> 00:22:30,433
My brother's kids.

338
00:22:31,726 --> 00:22:33,061
Adorable.

339
00:22:40,443 --> 00:22:43,571
- I got a job offer.
- Yeah? Where?

340
00:22:43,655 --> 00:22:46,574
Brad Petite. Special Advisor.

341
00:22:47,366 --> 00:22:49,286
From Hawaii.

342
00:22:49,368 --> 00:22:51,121
- Junior congressman?
- That's right.

343
00:22:51,205 --> 00:22:54,249
I like him. He's a good guy.
He's ambitious.

344
00:22:54,333 --> 00:22:56,459
He offered me a lot of money.

345
00:22:56,543 --> 00:22:59,046
- Yeah?
- Two-twenty.

346
00:22:59,129 --> 00:23:00,964
Jesus.

347
00:23:02,049 --> 00:23:04,718
That's more than I would ever make
at the White House.

348
00:23:07,679 --> 00:23:11,266
- You arrange the job?
- No.

349
00:23:11,350 --> 00:23:13,060
Did the president?

350
00:23:13,143 --> 00:23:15,645
- What are you talking about?
- Don't bullshit me, Seth.

351
00:23:15,729 --> 00:23:17,396
This is the first I'm hearing about it.

352
00:23:19,482 --> 00:23:21,609
Who's the senior congressman
from Hawaii?

353
00:23:22,903 --> 00:23:25,572
Chair of Appropriations.

354
00:23:25,655 --> 00:23:27,782
I know him,
I'm just drawing a blank right now.

355
00:23:28,449 --> 00:23:31,245
It's not him, it's a her.

356
00:23:31,328 --> 00:23:34,331
Francine Tenaka.
And if you don't know who Tenaka is,

357
00:23:34,413 --> 00:23:36,666
there's no reason you should know
who Brad Petite is,

358
00:23:36,750 --> 00:23:39,378
or that he's ambitious or a good guy.

359
00:23:39,460 --> 00:23:42,881
This job offer came from you
or the president.

360
00:23:42,964 --> 00:23:45,175
And I'm telling you that it didn't.

361
00:23:47,510 --> 00:23:49,221
Well, I'm turning it down.

362
00:23:50,138 --> 00:23:53,641
You tell the president that I'm ready
to come back whenever he needs me.

363
00:23:53,725 --> 00:23:55,810
I don't need training wheels.

364
00:24:10,075 --> 00:24:12,244
I need you to work on Birch
while you're here.

365
00:24:12,327 --> 00:24:15,038
See if you can get that list
of possible candidates.

366
00:24:15,122 --> 00:24:17,332
I don't think putting him down
the far end of the table's

367
00:24:17,416 --> 00:24:18,583
put him in a very chatty mood.

368
00:24:22,003 --> 00:24:25,215
Refrigeration.
Are you talking about refrigeration?

369
00:24:25,299 --> 00:24:27,634
- No.
- Re-bridge nations.

370
00:24:27,717 --> 00:24:30,845
We need to re-bridgenate ourselves
so we'll more trust each other.

371
00:24:30,929 --> 00:24:32,555
Da? Yes.

372
00:24:32,639 --> 00:24:34,933
Let's get these amendments
out of committee.

373
00:24:35,016 --> 00:24:36,393
Not all of them, just some of them.

374
00:24:36,475 --> 00:24:38,895
The Speaker would go ballistic
if I started meddling in the House.

375
00:24:38,979 --> 00:24:41,440
Not if it means he's going to battle
with the presumptive nominee.

376
00:24:41,564 --> 00:24:43,108
He knows where his bread is buttered.

377
00:24:43,191 --> 00:24:46,236
You shove your wife's recess appointment
down my throat, now you want my help?

378
00:24:46,320 --> 00:24:47,612
I had to fill the post.

379
00:24:47,695 --> 00:24:50,240
And you have a city
full of career diplomats.

380
00:24:50,324 --> 00:24:52,200
Her appointment was
a slap in the Senate's face.

381
00:24:52,284 --> 00:24:54,453
Let's not get hung up
on appointments, all right?

382
00:24:54,535 --> 00:24:56,704
Hector, whatever
you want me to sign, I'll sign.

383
00:24:56,788 --> 00:24:58,832
I will not hold a veto over your head.

384
00:24:58,915 --> 00:25:02,919
You can veto whatever you want.
Just helps our case in 2016.

385
00:25:03,003 --> 00:25:04,796
Excuse me.

386
00:25:10,469 --> 00:25:13,805
Which is more intoxicating,
this wine or Claire Underwood?

387
00:25:16,099 --> 00:25:17,476
How often do you use that line?

388
00:25:17,558 --> 00:25:20,687
- Not as often as you use yours.
- Which line is that?

389
00:25:21,688 --> 00:25:23,815
"Viktor, are you in love?"

390
00:25:26,609 --> 00:25:30,238
President Descoteaux told me you asked
him the same thing when he was here.

391
00:25:32,491 --> 00:25:35,869
I believe my husband quoted a Russian
author the night he gave that toast.

392
00:25:35,952 --> 00:25:38,872
- Don't say, uh... Tolstoy?
- Pushkin.

393
00:25:38,955 --> 00:25:43,751
"A deception that elevates us
is dearer than a host of low truths."

394
00:25:43,835 --> 00:25:47,130
Ah... He didn't make that toast.

395
00:25:48,173 --> 00:25:51,510
- No, he didn't.
- No, no.

396
00:25:51,592 --> 00:25:53,678
Tell me, do you
actually know your Pushkin,

397
00:25:53,761 --> 00:25:56,431
or did you just study up
before I arrived?

398
00:25:56,515 --> 00:25:58,641
Does it really matter?

399
00:26:01,436 --> 00:26:04,481
So, this is what he does?

400
00:26:04,563 --> 00:26:06,565
He leaves the seduction to you.

401
00:26:06,649 --> 00:26:10,237
Isn't there a...
a word for that in English? Um...

402
00:26:10,320 --> 00:26:13,698
- For what?
- "Pimping," yes?

403
00:26:13,781 --> 00:26:15,658
He's pimping you out.

404
00:26:17,702 --> 00:26:19,287
How charming you are.

405
00:26:19,371 --> 00:26:21,122
Thank you.

406
00:26:21,206 --> 00:26:24,251
And you make a much better First Lady
than ambassador,

407
00:26:24,334 --> 00:26:26,378
from what my people tell me.

408
00:26:29,172 --> 00:26:30,507
Only teasing.

409
00:26:31,425 --> 00:26:35,178
More wine... for the ambassador.

410
00:26:35,262 --> 00:26:36,721
Please.

411
00:26:48,483 --> 00:26:51,069
I'm gonna have to go
in a couple minutes.

412
00:26:51,152 --> 00:26:53,321
Ah!

413
00:26:53,405 --> 00:26:56,783
Mr. President, my gift for you.

414
00:26:57,658 --> 00:26:59,786
Best vodka in the world.

415
00:26:59,869 --> 00:27:02,289
Osobaya Sayanskaya.

416
00:27:03,790 --> 00:27:05,250
Solid gold.

417
00:27:05,333 --> 00:27:08,211
Each one of these bottles is 750,000.

418
00:27:09,879 --> 00:27:12,090
Now, a toast.

419
00:27:15,927 --> 00:27:19,097
To friendship, to good food,

420
00:27:19,180 --> 00:27:24,102
and to Leo Tolstoy, who said,

421
00:27:24,185 --> 00:27:27,314
"If you want to be happy, be."

422
00:27:27,397 --> 00:27:29,857
Drink!

423
00:27:34,988 --> 00:27:35,989
Ah!

424
00:27:36,072 --> 00:27:39,117
Now... you sniff your bread.

425
00:27:42,703 --> 00:27:44,914
Say "Nu."

426
00:27:44,998 --> 00:27:46,416
Nu!

427
00:27:46,500 --> 00:27:48,460
Then whistle.

428
00:27:48,543 --> 00:27:50,044
Sniff your sleeve.

429
00:27:51,838 --> 00:27:54,424
And... eat your pickle.

430
00:27:55,091 --> 00:27:57,760
Now, why we do all this?

431
00:27:58,928 --> 00:28:02,182
No one knows.

432
00:28:02,265 --> 00:28:03,517
Again!

433
00:28:03,600 --> 00:28:05,935
- Oh, no. Now, Mr. President.
- Mm, mm!

434
00:28:06,811 --> 00:28:09,648
Now, you, Mr. Vice President.

435
00:28:09,730 --> 00:28:12,859
- A toast!
- Oh! Uh... Um...

436
00:28:12,942 --> 00:28:15,612
Uh, to, uh... further cooperation

437
00:28:15,694 --> 00:28:19,824
between our two countries
and, uh... continued... uh...

438
00:28:19,907 --> 00:28:23,537
Oh, hell. Here's how!

439
00:28:26,665 --> 00:28:29,584
Again!

440
00:28:31,794 --> 00:28:35,298
Now, you... Mrs. Underwood.

441
00:28:37,842 --> 00:28:41,221
To President Petrov and his...

442
00:28:41,304 --> 00:28:44,391
little pickle.

443
00:28:44,474 --> 00:28:45,392
Drink!

444
00:28:50,480 --> 00:28:51,772
Again!

