486
00:32:41,544 --> 00:32:44,380
Hey!

487
00:32:44,464 --> 00:32:48,426
Well, I don't think we can end
the evening on a higher note,

488
00:32:48,509 --> 00:32:50,470
so I want to thank you all for coming,

489
00:32:50,553 --> 00:32:53,556
for the singing
and the dancing and the vodka.

490
00:32:53,640 --> 00:32:55,600
But most especially to my friend,
Peter Cincotti.

491
00:32:55,683 --> 00:32:56,684
Thank you.

492
00:32:56,768 --> 00:32:58,561
Coming all the way here
to the White House.

493
00:32:58,645 --> 00:33:01,648
Thank you. Thank you!
Thank you for a wonderful evening.

494
00:33:01,731 --> 00:33:04,609
Wonderful.
And thank you to you, Mr. Cincotti.

495
00:33:04,692 --> 00:33:05,902
Thank you. Thank you.

496
00:33:07,862 --> 00:33:09,739
Your motorcade is ready, Mr. President.

497
00:33:09,823 --> 00:33:10,949
I'll walk you out.

498
00:33:11,031 --> 00:33:13,326
But first, I want to show you something.
Come with me.

499
00:33:13,409 --> 00:33:15,328
- We'll be right down, Calista.
- Yes, sir.

500
00:33:16,830 --> 00:33:20,166
What if I get you transferred?
To some other agency.

501
00:33:20,249 --> 00:33:22,418
It doesn't matter
who I work for. He'll find a way.

502
00:33:27,214 --> 00:33:29,216
How much do you care about staying here?

503
00:33:29,300 --> 00:33:31,093
- What, DC?
- In this country.

504
00:33:31,177 --> 00:33:35,306
I'd have been long gone if they didn't
put a travel lock on my passport.

505
00:33:35,389 --> 00:33:37,141
So let's unlock it.

506
00:33:38,935 --> 00:33:42,271
Is that something you can do?
If I get you what you want?

507
00:33:43,230 --> 00:33:45,900
I need to know exactly where she is.

508
00:33:45,984 --> 00:33:49,403
Not a state. Not a city.
An address.

509
00:33:49,487 --> 00:33:53,616
If I use the Bureau's software and
get caught, I'll give them your name.

510
00:33:53,700 --> 00:33:55,535
I understand.

511
00:34:02,291 --> 00:34:03,334
All right.

512
00:34:04,669 --> 00:34:06,420
Tell me everything you know about her.

513
00:34:07,547 --> 00:34:08,923
Good night.

514
00:34:12,301 --> 00:34:14,637
- How about a night cap?
- Oh, it's late.

515
00:34:14,721 --> 00:34:17,348
And I haven't had that much vodka
since college.

516
00:34:17,431 --> 00:34:18,808
Tulane, right?

517
00:34:18,892 --> 00:34:21,019
So they tell me.
It's all a bit of a blur.

518
00:34:21,101 --> 00:34:23,521
What did you drink in school?
Hurricanes?

519
00:34:23,604 --> 00:34:26,858
Oh, we weren't barbarians.
Scotch, no ice.

520
00:34:26,941 --> 00:34:29,986
Oh... Two Chivas, neat.

521
00:34:33,614 --> 00:34:35,533
Cubans. Smuggled in.

522
00:34:35,616 --> 00:34:37,702
I thought you might
appreciate the irony.

523
00:34:37,785 --> 00:34:39,620
Ah. I do.

524
00:34:44,291 --> 00:34:47,420
Ah. And where does this lead?

525
00:34:47,503 --> 00:34:49,005
Basement entrance.

526
00:34:49,088 --> 00:34:51,507
The Nixon kids would
bring their dates up this way.

527
00:34:51,591 --> 00:34:54,844
Kennedy probably used it
for similar reasons.

528
00:34:54,928 --> 00:34:56,930
Well, you know, now that I'm divorced,

529
00:34:57,013 --> 00:34:59,766
I don't have to sneak anyone
in and out of the palace.

530
00:34:59,849 --> 00:35:02,727
They can come through the front door.
With some dignity.

531
00:35:02,810 --> 00:35:06,022
Well, dignity's a bit overrated
for a mistress, don't you think?

532
00:35:09,316 --> 00:35:14,405
Ah... you know,
a woman like your wife, for example,

533
00:35:14,488 --> 00:35:17,784
would certainly make it worthwhile.

534
00:35:17,867 --> 00:35:20,536
Do you kiss the wife
of every president you meet?

535
00:35:20,620 --> 00:35:23,957
Oh. Not every president's wife
looks like yours.

536
00:35:25,207 --> 00:35:28,168
I'd push him down the stairs
and light his broken body on fire

537
00:35:28,252 --> 00:35:32,131
just to watch it burn,
if it wouldn't start a world war.

538
00:35:32,214 --> 00:35:34,300
- May I?
- Of course.

539
00:35:39,097 --> 00:35:41,140
Well, do you think
they'll ever come around?

540
00:35:41,223 --> 00:35:43,017
Oh, I don't know.

541
00:35:43,101 --> 00:35:45,603
There'll be more summits,
a hundred CoDels.

542
00:35:45,686 --> 00:35:49,899
They'll ping-pong back and forth
for months before Petrov shows his hand.

543
00:35:53,736 --> 00:35:56,155
- What?
- Nothing.

544
00:35:56,238 --> 00:35:57,573
Tell me.

545
00:35:57,657 --> 00:36:00,910
I was just picturing Bugakov
playing ping-pong.

546
00:36:00,994 --> 00:36:04,831
Bugayev?

547
00:36:04,914 --> 00:36:07,207
Imagine him playing beer pong.

548
00:36:07,291 --> 00:36:09,836
Then these negotiations would be over.

549
00:36:09,919 --> 00:36:13,714
You are looking at the Delta Phi
beer pong champion.

550
00:36:13,798 --> 00:36:15,257
- No.
- Yes.

551
00:36:15,341 --> 00:36:17,343
Both sophomore and junior years.

552
00:36:17,426 --> 00:36:18,970
And what happened senior year?

553
00:36:19,053 --> 00:36:21,263
Well, I had to start studying
for law school.

554
00:36:23,307 --> 00:36:26,894
Well, I wasn't... a champion.

555
00:36:26,978 --> 00:36:29,229
- I wasn't too bad, though.
- You?

556
00:36:29,313 --> 00:36:31,941
Mm-hm.

557
00:36:32,025 --> 00:36:34,068
- I think we should play.
- What?

558
00:36:34,152 --> 00:36:35,277
Oh, you can't be serious.

559
00:36:35,361 --> 00:36:38,322
Excuse me? Can you ask housekeeping
to bring us some ping-pong balls, please?

560
00:36:38,405 --> 00:36:40,741
I have got to go home.

561
00:36:40,825 --> 00:36:42,952
We'll be playing by Harvard rules.

562
00:36:46,622 --> 00:36:50,543
You have to admire their fearlessness.

563
00:36:52,545 --> 00:36:54,881
None of them understand, do they?

564
00:36:55,548 --> 00:36:57,591
What it takes to govern.

565
00:36:57,675 --> 00:37:00,136
They scream and yell
and stomp their feet,

566
00:37:00,219 --> 00:37:02,847
but if they had to spend
just one day in our shoes,

567
00:37:02,930 --> 00:37:05,725
the weight we carry on our shoulders...

568
00:37:05,808 --> 00:37:09,395
Like, um... the Middle East?

569
00:37:10,771 --> 00:37:14,316
Oh, I know why we're here,
smoking our cigars.

570
00:37:16,861 --> 00:37:20,740
- And?
- You're not going to like it.

571
00:37:24,160 --> 00:37:26,495
Yes! Ha-ha!

572
00:37:26,579 --> 00:37:28,372
Drink up.

573
00:37:33,086 --> 00:37:34,712
Okay. For the Crimson.

574
00:37:39,633 --> 00:37:42,178
Damn!

575
00:37:49,685 --> 00:37:52,605
Yes! I still got it.

576
00:37:56,234 --> 00:37:58,194
You don't have to drink that.

577
00:37:58,277 --> 00:37:59,653
I accept your mercy.

578
00:38:00,821 --> 00:38:05,243
And I am going to leave
before you challenge me to a rematch.

579
00:38:05,325 --> 00:38:08,287
You're not even gonna give me a shot
at winning in my own house?

580
00:38:08,370 --> 00:38:11,165
First rule of diplomacy:
stop while you're ahead,

581
00:38:11,249 --> 00:38:15,253
which is what I should've done,
after that third vodka of Petrov's.

582
00:38:16,963 --> 00:38:19,006
What do you think of him?

583
00:38:19,715 --> 00:38:22,969
Petrov? I don't know.

584
00:38:24,178 --> 00:38:26,305
You were the one
who talked to him all night.

585
00:38:26,388 --> 00:38:28,141
Well, I didn't have much of a choice.

586
00:38:28,224 --> 00:38:30,726
So, not a fan?

587
00:38:30,810 --> 00:38:34,021
I think he's very intelligent.
And he has a charm.

588
00:38:34,105 --> 00:38:36,607
That kiss was... too much.

589
00:38:36,690 --> 00:38:39,026
No, that's just pushing buttons.

590
00:38:39,110 --> 00:38:42,196
The Russians love to do that.

591
00:38:42,280 --> 00:38:43,906
Good night.

592
00:38:45,074 --> 00:38:47,952
I don't think he's to be trusted, Cathy.

593
00:38:48,035 --> 00:38:51,205
Especially after tonight.
And it made me think...

594
00:38:53,582 --> 00:38:55,042
Go on.

595
00:38:56,002 --> 00:38:58,796
It made me wonder about Francis' plan.

596
00:38:58,879 --> 00:39:03,342
I'm not sure that it's a good idea
to be partnered with Petrov.

597
00:39:03,425 --> 00:39:07,180
In the meantime,
we alienate Israel and Palestine.

598
00:39:09,849 --> 00:39:14,312
Well... between you and me, I agree.

599
00:39:16,480 --> 00:39:18,316
Sit with me.

600
00:39:19,399 --> 00:39:21,443
What would you do differently?

601
00:39:23,779 --> 00:39:25,405
Well...

602
00:39:26,782 --> 00:39:29,952
If the goal is to get troops
into the Jordan Valley,

603
00:39:30,036 --> 00:39:33,747
well, then there's more than one way
to skin that cat.

604
00:39:33,831 --> 00:39:35,833
A multinational force?

605
00:39:35,916 --> 00:39:38,669
I would go through the UN.

606
00:39:38,752 --> 00:39:40,754
Peacekeeping?

607
00:39:40,838 --> 00:39:42,798
You wouldn't get past Russia's veto.

608
00:39:42,882 --> 00:39:47,345
There might be a way, but...

609
00:39:47,427 --> 00:39:51,515
you'd have a lot of responsibility
on your shoulders.

610
00:39:51,598 --> 00:39:54,935
Well, if you can give me guidance,
I'm sure I can handle it.

611
00:39:56,603 --> 00:40:01,150
There is precedent
with the Uniting for Peace Resolution.

612
00:40:01,234 --> 00:40:04,362
We used it to get around
the Russians for the Korean War.

613
00:40:09,700 --> 00:40:12,661
- The whole thing?
- From Poland to the UK.

614
00:40:12,745 --> 00:40:15,039
I want the entire
missile defense system gone.

615
00:40:15,122 --> 00:40:18,042
You know that's there to defend
against North Korea, against Iran.

616
00:40:18,125 --> 00:40:19,919
And far closer
to my borders than theirs.

617
00:40:20,002 --> 00:40:22,713
I'm asking for a few thousand troops
in the Jordan Valley.

618
00:40:22,796 --> 00:40:24,840
You're asking me to dismantle
Europe's defense system.

619
00:40:24,924 --> 00:40:27,385
What you're really asking for
is American forces

620
00:40:27,467 --> 00:40:29,136
just south of the Caucasus.

621
00:40:29,220 --> 00:40:31,555
You must have a strategic play in mind.

622
00:40:31,638 --> 00:40:33,682
This is about stability in the region.

623
00:40:33,766 --> 00:40:37,061
You're trying to consolidate
your foothold in the region. Hm?

624
00:40:37,144 --> 00:40:40,814
The Black Sea, Kazakhstan,
Chechnya, Crimea.

625
00:40:40,898 --> 00:40:44,651
So, please...
don't insult me with peace.

626
00:40:47,071 --> 00:40:52,785
Whatever your strategic goals may be,
the missile defense system is mine.

627
00:40:54,328 --> 00:40:58,207
Viktor, I invited you to Washington
with pure intentions,

628
00:40:58,291 --> 00:41:01,419
so that we could break bread
and learn to trust one another.

629
00:41:01,501 --> 00:41:04,546
Francis, I don't get softened up

630
00:41:04,630 --> 00:41:07,591
by a nice dinner
and dancing with a beautiful woman.

631
00:41:09,093 --> 00:41:10,886
You asked me what I want.

632
00:41:10,970 --> 00:41:13,055
Well... I told you.

633
00:41:16,475 --> 00:41:17,935
I'll tell you what.

634
00:41:18,018 --> 00:41:19,645
It's my turn to get some sleep.

635
00:41:19,728 --> 00:41:21,272
Let's attack all this with a fresh mind.

636
00:41:21,355 --> 00:41:23,983
We've barely smoked our cigars.

637
00:41:25,151 --> 00:41:28,321
We're not men of excess, though, are we?

638
00:41:29,822 --> 00:41:31,407
Aren't we?

639
00:41:35,202 --> 00:41:36,954
No, no.

640
00:41:37,037 --> 00:41:38,705
No, you're right.

641
00:41:41,292 --> 00:41:43,710
Enough smoke for one evening.

642
00:41:58,267 --> 00:42:00,186
What are you going to do?

643
00:42:01,061 --> 00:42:03,439
I don't know.

644
00:42:03,522 --> 00:42:05,399
Try to meet him halfway.

645
00:42:07,901 --> 00:42:10,446
Cathy and I were talking.

646
00:42:10,529 --> 00:42:12,865
Maybe the Israelis
and the Palestinians are right.

647
00:42:12,948 --> 00:42:15,117
We should consider starting with them.

648
00:42:15,201 --> 00:42:17,703
Use the United Nations
to put pressure on Russia.

649
00:42:17,786 --> 00:42:21,207
- How?
- Uniting for Peace.

650
00:42:21,290 --> 00:42:24,960
General Assembly overrides
a Russian veto in the Security Council.

651
00:42:25,044 --> 00:42:29,173
Well, that'll just antagonize them
even if it works. And it won't.

652
00:42:29,256 --> 00:42:32,009
Well, it might work.
Cathy seems to think it could.

653
00:42:32,092 --> 00:42:34,845
I thought you believed in this plan.

654
00:42:34,928 --> 00:42:38,307
We were just...
brainstorming alternatives.

655
00:42:38,391 --> 00:42:41,268
Well, I've worked too hard on it
just to abandon it.

656
00:42:42,895 --> 00:42:44,938
Okay, you know best.

657
00:43:07,044 --> 00:43:08,670
Do you mind?

658
00:43:10,464 --> 00:43:11,882
What?

659
00:43:11,965 --> 00:43:13,217
The light.

660
00:43:25,771 --> 00:43:27,356
Francis.

661
00:43:29,066 --> 00:43:31,110
He's a thug.

662
00:43:31,193 --> 00:43:33,028
Smart, but he's still a thug.

663
00:43:33,112 --> 00:43:34,821
Don't cower to him.

664
00:43:43,872 --> 00:43:48,919
Where I come from, we drop a raw egg
into some tomato juice and drink that.

665
00:43:49,002 --> 00:43:50,879
Luckily, I don't come from there.

666
00:43:52,548 --> 00:43:55,884
That's a perfect job for Doug.
I can't imagine why he'd turn it down.

667
00:43:55,968 --> 00:43:57,761
He thinks we were behind it.

668
00:43:57,844 --> 00:44:00,306
I told him we weren't,
but I don't think he believes me.

669
00:44:00,389 --> 00:44:02,266
Said he doesn't need training wheels.

670
00:44:02,349 --> 00:44:05,227
Well, I want you to still stop in
from time to time and see him.

671
00:44:05,311 --> 00:44:06,353
Yes, sir.

672
00:44:07,521 --> 00:44:10,232
Is the Secretary of Defense here?
Send him in.

673
00:44:12,692 --> 00:44:14,694
- Mr. President.
- We don't have much time.

674
00:44:14,778 --> 00:44:17,364
Petrov gets here in 90 minutes.
We need to talk Europe.

675
00:44:59,781 --> 00:45:02,242
The answer is yes.

676
00:45:03,118 --> 00:45:07,705
- To some, not all, of what you asked.
- I see.

677
00:45:07,789 --> 00:45:10,209
I'm prepared
to scale back significantly.

678
00:45:10,292 --> 00:45:14,838
Now, I have to speak to my team first
and my allies in NATO,

679
00:45:14,921 --> 00:45:17,257
but I'm confident that we can
do something meaningful

680
00:45:17,341 --> 00:45:19,510
in Poland and the Czech Republic.

681
00:45:19,593 --> 00:45:21,970
Now, our people
can work out the specifics.

682
00:45:22,054 --> 00:45:26,975
And whatever it is we decide
and agree on, the public cannot know.

683
00:45:31,564 --> 00:45:34,941
I woke up with the taste
of those cigars in my mouth.

684
00:45:35,901 --> 00:45:38,736
Thinking of Cuba and Kennedy.

685
00:45:38,820 --> 00:45:42,366
I won't be humiliated
the way Khrushchev was with Turkey.

686
00:45:42,449 --> 00:45:46,495
Well, you can't possibly compare what
I'm proposing to what happened then.

687
00:45:46,579 --> 00:45:49,582
I can only consider a partial
scale-back if you announce it.

688
00:45:52,585 --> 00:45:54,628
This press conference
is about the Jordan Valley.

689
00:45:54,712 --> 00:45:57,673
The most important thing about the
missiles is the scale-back, not the PR.

690
00:45:57,755 --> 00:46:00,092
My people would know
I walked away with something.

691
00:46:00,175 --> 00:46:04,680
And, by announcing it,
I can keep you to your word.

692
00:46:04,762 --> 00:46:07,474
I am more than
meeting you halfway, Viktor.

693
00:46:14,273 --> 00:46:17,859
You know what the best part
of the fall of the Soviet Union was?

694
00:46:18,818 --> 00:46:20,446
The cars.

695
00:46:21,488 --> 00:46:24,199
Have you ever been in, um... a Lada?

696
00:46:24,283 --> 00:46:25,783
Lada? No, I haven't.

697
00:46:25,867 --> 00:46:28,621
No? Oh. It's the worst car ever built.

698
00:46:28,704 --> 00:46:30,289
Tiny, little thing, you know.

699
00:46:30,372 --> 00:46:33,791
Your head would hit the ceiling
when you hit a pothole.

700
00:46:33,875 --> 00:46:37,003
And the heat never worked.

701
00:46:37,087 --> 00:46:38,589
And no air conditioning.

702
00:46:38,672 --> 00:46:41,675
You know, your skin would stick
to the seats in the summer.

703
00:46:41,759 --> 00:46:43,552
It was a coffin on wheels.

704
00:46:43,636 --> 00:46:48,140
But then, after the fall,
we got the Lexus.

705
00:46:49,516 --> 00:46:52,728
Temperature control.
Automatic windows.

706
00:46:52,810 --> 00:46:54,688
And so much room.

707
00:46:54,772 --> 00:46:57,775
First time I fucked my ex-wife,
in a Lexus.

708
00:46:57,899 --> 00:46:59,859
You could never do that in a Lada.

709
00:46:59,943 --> 00:47:02,404
No space. Huh?

710
00:47:02,488 --> 00:47:05,365
You see, Mr. President.

711
00:47:05,449 --> 00:47:07,200
I want the Lexus.

712
00:47:08,243 --> 00:47:10,663
And you're trying to sell me a Lada.

713
00:47:36,938 --> 00:47:39,358
I'll have them bring
your motorcade around.

714
00:47:42,569 --> 00:47:44,738
But the... press conference.

715
00:47:45,531 --> 00:47:49,284
Oh. Right!

716
00:47:49,368 --> 00:47:51,370
I'd completely forgotten.

717
00:47:52,454 --> 00:47:55,123
But I think we're gonna be okay
without one today.

718
00:47:57,167 --> 00:47:59,294
Have a safe journey home,
Mr. President.

719
00:48:08,679 --> 00:48:11,348
Thank you for your hospitality,
Mr. President.

720
00:48:21,775 --> 00:48:23,777
Give me the Secretary of State.

721
00:48:37,833 --> 00:48:40,918
The president will be speaking alone.
No joint conference.

722
00:48:43,296 --> 00:48:45,382
The president will be out shortly.

723
00:48:51,847 --> 00:48:54,433
Last night,
I had the pleasure of hosting

724
00:48:54,516 --> 00:48:57,436
some very special guests
here at the White House.

725
00:48:57,519 --> 00:49:00,439
True Russian patriots
who exhibit the very best

726
00:49:00,522 --> 00:49:02,816
that their country has to offer.

727
00:49:02,900 --> 00:49:05,778
Their names: Nadya Tolokonnikova,

728
00:49:05,861 --> 00:49:09,197
Masha Alyokhina and Pyotr Verzilov.

729
00:49:09,281 --> 00:49:12,785
As you're all aware,
they stood up to President Petrov,

730
00:49:12,868 --> 00:49:17,330
and forced him to listen to the truths
that he didn't want to hear.

731
00:49:18,791 --> 00:49:22,461
And, well, that had
a profound effect on me.

732
00:49:22,544 --> 00:49:25,631
